</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/iran-foreign-minister-araghchi-meeting-armenian-counterpart-yerevan.png" alt="Iran's Foreign Minister Abbas Araghchi attends a meeting with his Armenian counterpart in Yerevan" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>Iran's Foreign Minister Abbas Araghchi attends a meeting with his Armenian counterpart in Yerevan. Credits: AFP file</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Iran has made it clear that uranium enrichment is <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-17-04-2025-h1-1-non-negotiable" target="_blank">non-negotiable</a>. However, it is open to addressing related concerns and assures that the uranium stockpile will be used for peaceful purposes. Their Foreign Minister Abbas Araghchi asserted these views before talks with US envoy Richard Witkoff in Oman.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          This is the first high-level US-Iran engagement since President Trump exited the 2015 nuclear agreement and reinstated sanctions through his "<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-17-04-2025-h1-2-maximum-pressure" target="_blank">maximum pressure</a>" policy. Both sides described the initial talks as “constructive.” However, Witkoff later stressed that Iran must halt all enrichment, a demand Iran views as contradictory.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         Meanwhile, Iran maintains its “red lines” over enrichment rights, regional influence, and missile capabilities. The International Atomic Energy Agency reports Iran holds uranium enriched to 60%, well above the 2015 agreement’s limits. While President Pezeshkian expresses hope for a agreement, Supreme Leader Khamenei cautioned that talks might still fail. Parallely, Araghchi is also visiting Russia to <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-17-04-2025-h1-3-deliver-a-message" target="_blank">deliver a message</a> from Khamenei to President Putin. The talks will reconvene this weekend.</p>
        </mj-text>
