        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Wrong China</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;"><strong>Summary: Cambodia deports Taiwanese to Mainland China.</strong></p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Taiwan has condemned Cambodia for <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-17-04-2025-h3-5-sending-dozens-of-taiwanese" target="_blank">sending dozens of Taiwanese</a> nationals to China without notice or clarity. 
        </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">On March 31, Cambodian authorities arrested about 180 Taiwanese and seven Chinese nationals in a raid on a telecom fraud operation in Phnom Penh. Taiwan worked hard through its office in Ho Chi Minh City to get the Taiwanese nationals sent to Taipei. However, Cambodia deported nearly 190 suspects to Mainland China in three groups without sharing identities or confirming how many were Taiwanese.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Taiwan’s foreign ministry stated that Cambodia yielded to Beijing's pressure. They noted that Cambodia and Taiwan lack formal diplomatic ties and asked Cambodia to provide the complete list of deportees. The ministry also cautioned citizens about joining overseas telecom fraud schemes, often run by Chinese crime groups in Cambodia.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Since 2016, over 600 Taiwanese fraud suspects arrested abroad have been deported to China. Cambodia and China have developed deep political, economic, and military ties, further complicating Taiwan's position.</p>
        </mj-text>
    </mj-section>
