          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
            <strong>🇮🇳 India launches biggest-ever joint naval exercises in Africa</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">India, co-hosted by Tanzania, has started its <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-17-04-2025-br2-7-largest-joint-navel-exercise" target="_blank">largest joint naval exercise</a> with African nations, including Kenya, South Africa, and Mauritius. These six-day exercises strive to boost India's maritime influence in the Indian Ocean, counter piracy, and strengthen regional defense ties. This is especially critical due to China's rising military and commercial presence.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">India's growing role shows its ambition to become a regional security power and maintain a global presence in Africa. It has had cultural and economic connections to various East African nations in its history. However, it doesn’t match up to China in trade and military reach. These exercises will take place every two years. India's goal is to counter China's regional dominance and assert India's maritime leadership.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
